      "topic": "Basic Greetings",
      "explanation": "In German, greetings vary by time of day and formality. 'Guten Morgen' (good morning), 'Guten Tag' (good day), and 'Guten Abend' (good evening) are formal greetings. 'Hallo' is informal and can be used anytime.",
      "examples": [
        {
          "german": "Guten Morgen! Wie geht es Ihnen?",
          "english": "Good morning! How are you? (formal)"
        },
        {
          "german": "Hallo! Wie geht's?",
          "english": "Hello! How are you? (informal)"
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "topic": "Personal Pronouns",
      "explanation": "German has three persons in singular and plural. 'Ich' (I), 'du' (you informal), 'er/sie/es' (he/she/it), 'wir' (we), 'ihr' (you plural informal), 'sie/Sie' (they/you formal).",
      "examples": [
        {
          "german": "Ich heiße Maria. Wie heißt du?",
          "english": "My name is Maria. What's your name?"
        },
        {
          "german": "Er kommt aus Deutschland.",
          "english": "He comes from Germany."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "topic": "The Verb 'sein' (to be)",
      "explanation": "The verb 'sein' is irregular and essential for introductions. Conjugation: ich bin, du bist, er/sie/es ist, wir sind, ihr seid, sie/Sie sind.",
      "examples": [
        {
          "german": "Ich bin Student.",
          "english": "I am a student."
        },
        {
          "german": "Wir sind aus Berlin.",
          "english": "We are from Berlin."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
